      { id: 'D', text: 'State, Many-to-one Explanation: Overall explanation The refunds data is in the Refunds table. Till now, we have not joined the Refunds table to the rest of the data model. You can join the Refunds table to either the Date table or the State table as the Refunds table has the Week Key and the State Key. To calculate the % of refunded sales every week, we divide the refund data and the total sales data each week. If you join the Refunds table with the State table using State Key, it will be a many-to-one relationship as the Refunds table has duplicate State Key (the State Key and the Week Key are the dimension keys in the Refunds table, so we can deduce that the table stores refunds data for every Week and State combinations, if available). Since, by default, the filters travel only from the State to the Refunds table, we need to set the cross-filter direction to both (as we need sales values for calculating % Refund). This setup is great for calculating the % of Refunded sales for every State, as a State Key -> State Key relationship exists from Refunds to State and State to Sales. But it is not suitable for calculating the % of Refunded sales every week. For example: 1. If the measure is filtered by Week Key (in the Refunds table), and since the Week Key is not involved in a relationship, 2. all State Keys where a refund has occurred during that week will be filtered. This State Key filter travels all the way to the Sales table. 3. So, the Week does not filter the Sales, rather the States where a refund has occurred during the week filter the sales. On the other hand, if you join the Refunds table to the State table, it will be a many-to-many relationship since we are joining the Week, not the Date Key from the Date table. The many-to-many relationship requires only the Refunds table to filter the Date table, so a bidirectional cross-filter is not necessary. This setup works great for calculating the % of refunded sales every week as there is a relationship between the Refunds and the Date table on Week Key. For example: 1. Once a Week is filtered, 2. the relationship between Sales and Date on the Date Key ensures that only the dates in those weeks filter the Sales table, 3. producing the correct result. So, Question 1 -> Date and Question 2 -> Many-tomany. Option A is the correct answer. But note that if you try to calculate the % of refunded sales for every State, it will not work. The reasoning is the same (discussed below). If the measure is filtered by State Key (in the Refunds table), and since the State Key is not involved in a relationship, all weeks where a refund has occurred for that State will be filtered. So, the state will not filter the Sales, rather the weeks where a refund has occurred for that State filters the sales. I have attached the Excel data source too in the below link. Download and filter the data and check for yourself. PBIX File Link: https://github.com/ravikiran-srini/PL-300-PracticeTest-Exam-PBIX-lab-files/blob/main/GenAffair%2C%20Inc.%20Case%20Study%20-%205.zip' }
